an rain forest between 2007 and 2008. In this pathbreaking book, Charles L. Briggs and Clara Mantini-Briggs relay the nightmarish and difficult experiences of doctors, patients, parents, local leaders, healers, and epidemiologists; detail how journalists first created a smoke screen, then projected the epidemic worldwide; discuss the Chávez government's hesitant and sometimes ambivalent reactions; and narrate the eventual diagnosis of bat-transmitted rabies. The book provides a new framework for analyzing how the uneven distribution of rights to produce and circulate knowledge about health are wedded at the hip with health inequities. By recounting residents' quest to learn why their children died and documenting their creative approaches to democratizing health, the authors open up new ways to address some of global health's most intractable problems.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCommunicable diseases in childrenzVenezuelazDelta AmacuroxHistoryy21st century. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezVenezuelazDelta AmacuroxHistoryy21st century. 0aEpidemicszVenezuelazDelta AmacuroxHistoryy21st century. 0aWarao childrenxDiseaseszVenezuelazDelta AmacuroxHistoryy21st century. 4aAAA Book Prize winners. 4aAAA New Millennium Book Award. 4aSociety for Medical Anthropology book awards. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aMantini-Briggs, Clara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374398zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374398.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aE